  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The sentence 'The __________ is ___ times the mass/capacity/volume of the __________' supports understanding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613609Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3963-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Comparisons of measure can be represented as multiplication equations."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613615Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3963-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Division can be represented as multiplication by a unit fraction"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613622Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3850-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are lots of real life examples where you can find lines of symmetry, for example in flags."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613629Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3850-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When a pattern is symmetrical, you can fold along its line of symmetry and the two halves will match exactly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613636Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3637-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A part must be part of a whole."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613789Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3637-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "If __ is the whole then __ is part of the whole."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613795Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3637-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The whole can be different in different situations."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613803Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4078-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the minuend and subtrahend are both increased by the same amount, the difference stays the same."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613813Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4078-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the minuend and subtrahend are both decreased by the same amount, the difference stays the same."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613820Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4078-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A number line can be used to represent the 'same difference' generalisation."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613832Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3907-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Counting backwards can continue past zero and include negative numbers."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613953Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3907-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Positioning negative numbers on marked and partially marked number lines."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613960Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3907-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Understanding that fractions and decimals can be positive or negative."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.613967Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4180-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In fractions equivalent to a half, the numerator is half the value of the denominator."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614012Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4180-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When the numerator is more than half the value of the denominator, the fraction is greater than a half."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614019Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4180-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When the numerator is less than half the value of the denominator, the fraction is less than a half."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614025Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3624-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Multiples of 8 are all multiples of 4 but not all multiples of 4 are multiples of 8"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614033Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3624-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Multiples of 8 are double the multiples of 4"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614039Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3624-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Multiples of 4 are half the multiples of 8"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614046Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3979-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use scaling to convert the decimal fraction to a whole number then multiply; use scaling to adjust the product."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614419Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3979-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If using short multiplication with decimal fractions, align the decimal point in the decimal fraction and product."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614429Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4006-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If 3 groups of 4 are equal to 12 then 3 groups of 4 fifths are equal to 12 fifths."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614437Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4006-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "If the product is an improper fraction you can convert it to a mixed number."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614444Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4006-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The numerator of the fraction is multiplied by the whole number and the denominator remains the same."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614451Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3905-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The negative or minus sign in front of a number shows that it is a negative value."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614458Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7400-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the product of the ones digits is greater than 10, you regroup ten ones into one ten."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614706Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7400-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the product of the ones digits is greater than ten, the partial product will be a 2-digit number."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614713Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7400-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are similarities between the representations of multiplication."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614720Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7401-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the product of the ones digit is greater than 10, you regroup ten ones into one ten."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614765Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7401-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Record the additional ten or tens as a small digit to be added in with the tens."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614772Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7401-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Short multiplication results in only one product being recorded."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614786Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7401-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are similarities and differences between the expanded recording and short multiplication."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614793Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3646-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The whole has been divided into __ equal parts."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614869Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3646-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Each equal part is one-__ of the whole."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614876Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3646-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Fractions can be represented in different ways including names and notation."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.614882Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3992-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To simplify a multiplication calculation, you can change the order of the factors."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.615268Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3992-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """To simplify a multiplication calculation you can group the factors in different ways."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.615275Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3639-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Equal parts do not have to look the same."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.615389Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3639-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Equal parts of a whole can be different shapes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.615395Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3639-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A whole can be made from equal parts that are different shapes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.615402Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3863-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "If the dividend is a multiple of the divisor, there will be no remainder."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.615624Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3863-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "If the remainder is greater than the divisor, another equal group can be made."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.615630Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3863-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "If the remainder is known, the possibilities for a missing divisor can be found."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.615636Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3863-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "If the divisor is known, the possibilities for a missing remainder can be found."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.615643Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3863-5
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "This knowledge can help when solving missing number equations."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.615649Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4063-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The same whole can be composed in different ways."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616351Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4063-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Different ways of composing the whole are equivalent."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616357Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4063-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Expressions can be used to express the combinations of different parts of the whole."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616364Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7607-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the multiplicative relationship between the numerator and denominator is the same, the fractions will be equivalent"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616370Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7607-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If a fraction is equivalent to a half, the numerator will be half the value of the denominator"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616376Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7607-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If a fraction is equivalent to fifth, the denominator will be 5 times the value of the numerator"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616383Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4041-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If 1 km is equal to one lot of 1,000 m, then 3 km is equal to three lots of 1,000 m, which is 3,000 m"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616523Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4041-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "If 1 l = 1,000 ml, then 4 l = 4 x 1,000 ml = 4,000 ml"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616530Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3917-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Short multiplication is another way of representing 2-digit by 1-digit multiplication."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616536Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3917-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are similarities between the representations of multiplication."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616543Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3917-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Arranging the factors in columns allows you to organise the partial products into a column addition."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616550Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3638-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Parts can be equal or unequal in size."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616920Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3638-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are __ equal parts in the whole."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616926Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3638-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are __ unequal parts in the whole."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.616933Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4046-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are 60 minutes in an hour."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617248Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4046-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are 24 hours in a day."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617258Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4046-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are 12 months in a year."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617264Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4046-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are 365 days in most years."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617271Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3911-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Negative data values can be recorded by extending the axes beyond zero"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617277Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3876-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Numbers are recorded in columns with the same value digits in each column."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617905Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3876-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Start with the smallest value column in case numbers need to be regrouped or exchanged."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617914Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3876-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the value of a digit in the minuend is greater than the same digit in the subtrahend, you will need to exchange."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617921Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3876-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Make sure that any regrouped numbers are added in with others of the same value."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.617926Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3915-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When you partition and multiply the ones and then the tens you get partial products."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618230Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3915-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "When you add the partial products you calculate the overall product."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618236Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3915-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Partitioning helps you to organise multiplication."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618245Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3909-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Differences between values are always positive"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618254Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3909-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Calculating differences across zero is the same as bridging through zero"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618261Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3860-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Multiplication facts can be used to solve division equations and problems."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618356Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3860-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In cases with a remainder, the largest multiple that is less than or equal to the dividend can be used."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618401Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3860-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """This indicates which multiplication fact should be used to find the number of equal groups."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618408Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3860-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When the largest multiple is found, it is subtracted from the dividend to find the remainder."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618414Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3966-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Change can be described using multiplication or division. Division can be represented as multiplication by a fraction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618550Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3966-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The sentence 'The __________ is ___ times the size of the __________' supports us to describe a comparison or change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618556Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3966-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If units are different, we should convert so that they are the same - this supports us to calculate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618562Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3966-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To find a missing factor, we can divide the product by the known factor."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618568Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3654-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When comparing unit fractions, the greater the denominator, the smaller the fraction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618789Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3654-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When comparing unit fractions, the smaller the denominator, the larger the fraction."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618795Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3654-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Equal parts may not look the same."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618801Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3914-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Place value resources can be used to represent multiplication of a 2-digit by a 1-digit number."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618874Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3914-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Regroup from the ones to the tens if the product of the tens is greater than 10"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618880Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3914-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Regroup from the tens to the hundreds if the product of the tens is greater than 100"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618887Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3912-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Scales on graphs and coordinate grids are the same as number lines."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618893Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3912-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Number lines model bridging through zero."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618899Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4072-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A representation helps to make sense of an equation or problem."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618905Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4072-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A bar model can be used to help solve additive problems."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618914Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4072-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A part-whole model can be used to identify the equation needed to solve an additive problem."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.618921Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3729-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are two 500s in 1,000"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.619140Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3729-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There are four 250s in 1,000"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.619146Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3729-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Knowing how many 500s and 250s 1,000 is composed of helps to interpret scales and measures."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.619152Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3722-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Look at the thousands digit to compare and order if they are different."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.619394Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3722-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the thousands digits are the same, look at the hundreds digit to compare and order if they are different."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.619400Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3722-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the thousands and hundreds digits are the same, look at the tens digit to compare and order if they are different."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.619406Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3722-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the thousands, hundreds and tens digits are the same, look at the ones digit to compare and order the numbers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.619412Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7404-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Use times tables and place value to estimate the product of a 2-digit by a 1-digit multiplication."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.619419Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7404-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Use expanded short multiplication to multiply a 2-digit by a 1-digit number."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.619425Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7404-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Use short multiplication to multiply a 2-digit by a 1-digit number."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.619431Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7403-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the product of the single digit and the tens number is greater than 100 then you regroup ten tens into one hundred."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.620580Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7403-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Record the additional hundred or hundreds in the hundreds column, one column to the left of the tens digits."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.620586Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7403-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Short multiplication results in only one product being recorded."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.620592Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-7403-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are similarities and differences between the expanded recording and short multiplication."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.620598Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3657-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If two parts are the same size, but a different fraction of the whole, the whole with the most parts will be greater."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621045Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3657-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If two parts are different, but are the same fraction of the whole, the whole with the larger part will be greater."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621051Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3657-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the size of the part and the fraction of the whole are different, we need to calculate to determine which is greater."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621057Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4047-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Use known units of measure and their equivalents to solve problems"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621334Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3857-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A multiplication equation can be written to solve division problems."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621341Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3857-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A division equation can be written to solve division problems."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621347Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3857-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The number of equal groups in a number can be found by counting forwards."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621352Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3857-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The number of equal groups in a number can be found by counting backwards."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621358Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3857-5
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Counting forwards is usually easier because multiplication facts can be used to help."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621364Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4018-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The whole has been divided into __ equal parts and there are __ in each part."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621396Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4018-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Use representations of sets of objects to divide them into equal parts."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621402Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-4018-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Count how many objects are in each equal part."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621408Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3666-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A fraction is a number and has an exact position on a number line."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621414Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3666-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Fractions can be ordered and positioned on a number line."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621420Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3666-3
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Unit and non-unit proper fractions lie between 0 and 1 on a number line."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621426Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3666-4
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "In a proper fraction, the numerator is less than the denominator."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621450Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3906-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Negative numbers are below zero on a vertical scale"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621694Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3906-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Negative numbers are to the left of zero on a horizontal scale"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621699Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3640-1
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Parts of the same sized whole can be compared."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.621705Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oak:keylearningpoint-lesson-3640-2
  a oakcurric:KeyLearningPoint ;
